WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:11.670 --> 00:00:13.420
RACHEL SMITH: Please
welcome J.L. Collins.

00:00:13.420 --> 00:00:17.631
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:17.631 --> 00:00:18.630
J.L. COLLINS: Thank you.

00:00:18.630 --> 00:00:19.838
RACHEL SMITH: You're welcome.

00:00:21.900 --> 00:00:26.100
So my first question for
you, the title of your book

00:00:26.100 --> 00:00:28.170
is "The Simple Path to Wealth."

00:00:28.170 --> 00:00:29.010
J.L. COLLINS: It is.

00:00:29.010 --> 00:00:32.100
RACHEL SMITH: And it's a roadmap
to financial independence

00:00:32.100 --> 00:00:33.580
and a rich, free life.

00:00:33.580 --> 00:00:36.630
So what does wealth
mean to you, and how

00:00:36.630 --> 00:00:38.495
is it tied to a free life?

00:00:38.495 --> 00:00:40.620
J.L. COLLINS: Well, I
suppose we could look at that

00:00:40.620 --> 00:00:42.520
in two different directions.

00:00:42.520 --> 00:00:46.230
So if we think about the
psychological part of it,

00:00:46.230 --> 00:00:48.660
to me, personally,
what wealth represents

00:00:48.660 --> 00:00:52.730
is security and freedom.

00:00:52.730 --> 00:00:56.590
So security to protect you
from what the world can

00:00:56.590 --> 00:00:59.890
throw at you, and freedom to
chart your own path in a way

00:00:59.890 --> 00:01:02.920
that you couldn't do
without the resource.

00:01:02.920 --> 00:01:04.420
On the financial
point of view, I

00:01:04.420 --> 00:01:09.130
suppose when I think about
what the benchmarks are

00:01:09.130 --> 00:01:11.860
for are you wealthy or
not, have you achieved

00:01:11.860 --> 00:01:14.830
financial independence
or not, what

00:01:14.830 --> 00:01:18.270
has come to be called the
4% rule is a good guideline.

00:01:18.270 --> 00:01:20.980
That comes out of a thing
called the Trinity study.

00:01:20.980 --> 00:01:22.840
And without
belaboring that point,

00:01:22.840 --> 00:01:25.810
it simply suggests
that if you have

00:01:25.810 --> 00:01:30.380
enough assets that
4% of that amount

00:01:30.380 --> 00:01:32.960
can cover your
annual expenses, you

00:01:32.960 --> 00:01:35.774
can consider yourself
financially independent.

00:01:35.774 --> 00:01:37.940
So you can work at it from
two different directions.

00:01:37.940 --> 00:01:41.480
You could say, well, I have a
million dollars, so 4% of that

00:01:41.480 --> 00:01:43.340
is $40,000.

00:01:43.340 --> 00:01:45.816
Can I live on $40,000
a year or not?

00:01:45.816 --> 00:01:47.690
And therein lies the
answer to your question.

00:01:47.690 --> 00:01:50.210
Or you can look at it
from the other direction.

00:01:50.210 --> 00:01:53.990
You can say, you know, I
need $40,000 to live on.

00:01:53.990 --> 00:01:57.470
So how much do I need to
be financially independent?

00:01:57.470 --> 00:02:00.920
You multiply $40,000
by, as it happens, 25,

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:03.200
you get a million dollars,
and there's your answer.

00:02:03.200 --> 00:02:07.845
So it really depends
on what your needs are.

00:02:07.845 --> 00:02:09.720
RACHEL SMITH: And why
is it important to keep

00:02:09.720 --> 00:02:10.949
the path simple?

00:02:10.949 --> 00:02:12.990
I think there are a
lot of folks tuning in

00:02:12.990 --> 00:02:15.030
or folks in the
audience who have read

00:02:15.030 --> 00:02:17.720
financial independence
books, and maybe their eyes

00:02:17.720 --> 00:02:19.470
roll back in their
head, because they just

00:02:19.470 --> 00:02:20.594
can't make sense of it all.

00:02:20.594 --> 00:02:22.860
So why is it important
to keep it simple?

00:02:22.860 --> 00:02:24.651
J.L. COLLINS: Well,
that's one good reason.

00:02:26.540 --> 00:02:29.160
But the reason that I
prefer keeping it simple

00:02:29.160 --> 00:02:31.590
is simple is simply
more powerful.

00:02:31.590 --> 00:02:34.642
Simple is what gets
you the best results.

00:02:34.642 --> 00:02:36.600
And in this case, when
I talk about simplicity,

00:02:36.600 --> 00:02:41.310
I'm talking about index funds
and specifically broad-based

00:02:41.310 --> 00:02:45.310
stock and then bond index funds
when you bring them into it.

00:02:45.310 --> 00:02:48.100
There are a lot of reasons that
simplicity is an advantage.

00:02:48.100 --> 00:02:49.770
It keeps your costs low.

00:02:49.770 --> 00:02:51.510
It keeps your life simpler.

00:02:51.510 --> 00:02:54.900
It makes things, when the time
comes, easier on your heirs.

00:02:54.900 --> 00:02:59.250
But the most important thing
is it is the most powerful way

00:02:59.250 --> 00:03:01.680
to reach financial independence.

00:03:01.680 --> 00:03:03.870
People who come to
my blog are always--

00:03:03.870 --> 00:03:06.330
I get two kinds of
readers of my blog.

00:03:06.330 --> 00:03:08.730
People who are really
into this stuff and they

00:03:08.730 --> 00:03:11.040
always want to
tinker, and that's not

00:03:11.040 --> 00:03:13.170
who I'm really writing for.

00:03:13.170 --> 00:03:14.940
I'm writing for people
like my daughter

00:03:14.940 --> 00:03:17.370
who knows that it's
important, but she

00:03:17.370 --> 00:03:19.770
has other things that she'd
rather do with her life

00:03:19.770 --> 00:03:23.440
than fixate on
finances and investing.

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:25.350
And so when you
have a simple path,

00:03:25.350 --> 00:03:27.810
you can just get a
couple of things right.

00:03:27.810 --> 00:03:29.630
You'll have a very
powerful performance.

00:03:29.630 --> 00:03:32.850
You will outperform the vast
majority of professionals

00:03:32.850 --> 00:03:33.620
out there.

00:03:33.620 --> 00:03:37.320
And I am fond of saying to
those people who want to tinker,

00:03:37.320 --> 00:03:40.770
if I thought there was a way
to successfully tinker and do

00:03:40.770 --> 00:03:43.690
better, then that's what I would
have written the book about.

00:03:43.690 --> 00:03:48.910
And in fact, I wasted a couple
of decades trying to find that.

00:03:48.910 --> 00:03:52.590
RACHEL SMITH: So you have
a blog, jlcollinsnh.com.

00:03:52.590 --> 00:03:56.434
If folks are interested
in your content,

00:03:56.434 --> 00:03:58.350
should they begin with
your blog or your book?

00:04:00.219 --> 00:04:02.760
J.L. COLLINS: I would suggest
that if you don't know anything

00:04:02.760 --> 00:04:07.080
about me or this concept, I
would go first to the blog.

00:04:07.080 --> 00:04:10.080
And I would go to-- there's a
button at the top called Stock

00:04:10.080 --> 00:04:12.240
Series, and the
blog is best known

00:04:12.240 --> 00:04:14.910
for my stock series of posts.

00:04:14.910 --> 00:04:16.910
And when you click
on that button,

00:04:16.910 --> 00:04:20.790
that will take you
to an introduction.

00:04:20.790 --> 00:04:22.860
And in that
introduction is a link

00:04:22.860 --> 00:04:26.670
to what I think is the best
review of my stock series

00:04:26.670 --> 00:04:27.790
that's been done--

00:04:27.790 --> 00:04:29.790
and not best because
it's most favorable,

00:04:29.790 --> 00:04:32.040
but in my view most accurate.

00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:34.740
So you can click over to that
and read that brief review.

00:04:34.740 --> 00:04:37.041
And after reading it,
you'll know very clearly

00:04:37.041 --> 00:04:38.790
whether this is going
to resonate with you

00:04:38.790 --> 00:04:40.456
or not and whether
it's worth your time.

00:04:40.456 --> 00:04:42.450
So I'd start there,
and then I would

00:04:42.450 --> 00:04:44.255
read a couple of the posts.

00:04:44.255 --> 00:04:46.350
And then if you
like what you read,

00:04:46.350 --> 00:04:48.570
you can consider
going on to the book.

00:04:48.570 --> 00:04:52.860
There is nothing in the
book that's not in the blog,

00:04:52.860 --> 00:04:54.420
so you can get all
the information

00:04:54.420 --> 00:04:56.610
just by staying on the blog.

00:04:56.610 --> 00:04:58.560
The book is more concise.

00:04:58.560 --> 00:05:01.680
It's better organized,
because the post and the blog

00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:03.540
came organically as
they occurred to me

00:05:03.540 --> 00:05:04.795
or were suggested.

00:05:04.795 --> 00:05:07.170
And the book has the advantage
of being better organized.

00:05:07.170 --> 00:05:09.880
It's more concise.

00:05:09.880 --> 00:05:12.040
I spent more time
polishing the writing so,

00:05:12.040 --> 00:05:13.880
I hope that the writing
is more polished.

00:05:13.880 --> 00:05:16.200
But you'll make
the judge of that.

00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:17.290
RACHEL SMITH: Got it.

00:05:17.290 --> 00:05:21.430
And thinking back to the early
days of your own investment

00:05:21.430 --> 00:05:24.190
history, how did you
learn all this stuff?

00:05:24.190 --> 00:05:26.929
How did you learn to invest?

00:05:26.929 --> 00:05:28.720
J.L. COLLINS: Well, I
did it the hard way--

00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:31.120
trial and error.

00:05:31.120 --> 00:05:39.480
I spent, as I alluded to
earlier, decades trying

00:05:39.480 --> 00:05:43.075
to do things that were not--

00:05:43.075 --> 00:05:47.420
what's seductive about
this is that they were

00:05:47.420 --> 00:05:50.690
subpar but not bad performance.

00:05:50.690 --> 00:05:52.910
I tell people that long
before I discovered

00:05:52.910 --> 00:05:55.090
or embraced indexed
investing, I'd

00:05:55.090 --> 00:05:56.450
reach financial independence.

00:05:56.450 --> 00:06:00.020
So I reached financial
independence by picking stocks

00:06:00.020 --> 00:06:03.890
and picking mutual fund
managers-- active managers--

00:06:03.890 --> 00:06:06.800
who could pick stocks or
thought they could pick stocks.

00:06:06.800 --> 00:06:07.820
So it can be done.

00:06:07.820 --> 00:06:10.020
The problem with it is
it's more expensive.

00:06:10.020 --> 00:06:11.250
It's more time consuming.

00:06:11.250 --> 00:06:13.490
It's not as effective
as indexing.

00:06:13.490 --> 00:06:16.160
So I would have been
much better off if I'd

00:06:16.160 --> 00:06:18.710
discovered indexing earlier.

00:06:18.710 --> 00:06:21.390
The great irony is
that Jack Bogle,

00:06:21.390 --> 00:06:24.050
who is the founder of
Vanguard and the inventor

00:06:24.050 --> 00:06:27.260
of the first index fund
available to the public,

00:06:27.260 --> 00:06:30.380
launched that fund in 1975.

00:06:30.380 --> 00:06:34.700
1975 was the first year
I started investing.

00:06:34.700 --> 00:06:37.550
I never heard of Jack Bogle
or Vanguard or index funds

00:06:37.550 --> 00:06:38.960
when I started.

00:06:38.960 --> 00:06:41.480
It was 10 years before
I heard of them,

00:06:41.480 --> 00:06:44.810
and then it took me a
disturbingly long time

00:06:44.810 --> 00:06:47.720
to embrace it.

00:06:47.720 --> 00:06:52.016
So people say, how do
you know all this stuff?

00:06:52.016 --> 00:06:53.390
I it's, well,
because I made just

00:06:53.390 --> 00:06:55.098
about-- if you can
think of a mistake you

00:06:55.098 --> 00:06:58.290
can make in investing,
I've probably made it.

00:06:58.290 --> 00:07:01.527
So to the extent that I know
anything is from my mistakes.

00:07:01.527 --> 00:07:03.110
RACHEL SMITH: So
speaking of mistakes,

00:07:03.110 --> 00:07:06.080
what do you think was working
in your favor versus working

00:07:06.080 --> 00:07:09.232
against you as you were trying
to figure this out on your own?

00:07:09.232 --> 00:07:11.690
J.L. COLLINS: Well, I think
the main thing that was working

00:07:11.690 --> 00:07:15.740
against me at the time and that
is working against everybody

00:07:15.740 --> 00:07:20.390
listening to this is there
is a large industry--

00:07:20.390 --> 00:07:25.940
Wall Street-- whose drumbeat is
counter to our best interests.

00:07:25.940 --> 00:07:29.990
And it is based on making
this as complex as possible,

00:07:29.990 --> 00:07:32.690
putting out a siren
song that you, too,

00:07:32.690 --> 00:07:34.340
can be Warren Buffett.

00:07:34.340 --> 00:07:36.970
You, too, can pick stocks.

00:07:36.970 --> 00:07:39.000
You, too, can
outperform the indexes--

00:07:42.120 --> 00:07:45.330
only if you're willing to
pay us for the privilege.

00:07:45.330 --> 00:07:47.280
And that's a very
seductive message,

00:07:47.280 --> 00:07:50.280
because everybody wants to think
that they can be above average

00:07:50.280 --> 00:07:51.981
and outperform.

00:07:51.981 --> 00:07:54.480
RACHEL SMITH: You're in a room
full of above average people.

00:07:54.480 --> 00:07:56.490
J.L. COLLINS: Well, right.

00:07:56.490 --> 00:08:00.450
But maybe not in investing.

00:08:00.450 --> 00:08:03.990
Now, the irony is if you
invest in index funds--

00:08:03.990 --> 00:08:06.510
and, of course, the slam
that active managers

00:08:06.510 --> 00:08:09.390
put against index investing
is that you will only

00:08:09.390 --> 00:08:12.320
get average returns.

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:15.590
That's a little bit misleading,
because yes, the index

00:08:15.590 --> 00:08:18.930
gives you the return
of the market overall.

00:08:18.930 --> 00:08:21.620
But that return is
far above average.

00:08:21.620 --> 00:08:26.330
Index investing, based on the
research that has been done,

00:08:26.330 --> 00:08:29.900
outperforms-- depending on
what numbers you look at--

00:08:29.900 --> 00:08:36.260
80% to 85% of active managers
over a 15 year period of time.

00:08:36.260 --> 00:08:39.440
If you research out
30 years, the number

00:08:39.440 --> 00:08:42.950
of active managers who
can outperform the index

00:08:42.950 --> 00:08:45.770
is less than 1%.

00:08:45.770 --> 00:08:48.790
That's statistically zero.

00:08:48.790 --> 00:08:51.280
So when you invest in
the index and you're

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:54.610
getting the average
performance of the market,

00:08:54.610 --> 00:08:57.430
you're actually getting
the best performance

00:08:57.430 --> 00:09:01.470
that you can expect
by a long shot.

00:09:01.470 --> 00:09:06.146
RACHEL SMITH: And so what
was working in your favor?

00:09:06.146 --> 00:09:08.020
J.L. COLLINS: I think
was working in my favor

00:09:08.020 --> 00:09:12.070
is I continued
being curious, and I

00:09:12.070 --> 00:09:13.720
continued trying
different things,

00:09:13.720 --> 00:09:15.760
and I continued researching.

00:09:15.760 --> 00:09:18.130
And indexing, which was
first put in front of me

00:09:18.130 --> 00:09:21.200
in 1985 by a good
friend of mine--

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:23.920
there's something about it
that is very counter-intuitive,

00:09:23.920 --> 00:09:26.680
and I think particularly
for smart people

00:09:26.680 --> 00:09:29.500
like the people in this room
and the people listening.

00:09:29.500 --> 00:09:31.690
Because you look
at it, and you say,

00:09:31.690 --> 00:09:36.740
well, indexing says I buy
every stock in the index.

00:09:36.740 --> 00:09:41.210
And yet, if I can only just
not buy the obvious dogs,

00:09:41.210 --> 00:09:42.810
I'll outperform.

00:09:42.810 --> 00:09:45.980
I mean, outperforming seems
like it should be so simple.

00:09:45.980 --> 00:09:47.520
But the problem with that--

00:09:47.520 --> 00:09:50.570
or even if I just buy the
top performers and not

00:09:50.570 --> 00:09:53.240
even buy the mediocre or
the low performing ones.

00:09:53.240 --> 00:09:55.100
Obviously, I'm
going to outperform.

00:09:55.100 --> 00:09:56.750
And yet, you look
at that research

00:09:56.750 --> 00:09:59.309
that says that doesn't happen.

00:09:59.309 --> 00:10:01.100
And of course, the
reason it doesn't happen

00:10:01.100 --> 00:10:04.580
is today's dogs are sometimes
tomorrow's great turnaround

00:10:04.580 --> 00:10:06.200
success stories.

00:10:06.200 --> 00:10:09.350
And those that are flying
high are the stories

00:10:09.350 --> 00:10:11.270
of how they crash and burn.

00:10:11.270 --> 00:10:14.420
So there is no way
to know what is going

00:10:14.420 --> 00:10:18.770
to happen with specific stocks,
and it is just way too easy

00:10:18.770 --> 00:10:21.292
to guess wrong.

00:10:21.292 --> 00:10:23.000
RACHEL SMITH: So one
thing that struck me

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:27.410
about your blog and your book
is how specific the advice is.

00:10:27.410 --> 00:10:31.820
So in other books or websites
I've tried reading in the past,

00:10:31.820 --> 00:10:33.320
the advice was
always really vague,

00:10:33.320 --> 00:10:35.990
like invest in mutual funds.

00:10:35.990 --> 00:10:39.620
And it would leave me thinking,
well, which one, and how much?

00:10:39.620 --> 00:10:43.400
So why do you think other
authors' advice is not

00:10:43.400 --> 00:10:45.385
very specific?

00:10:45.385 --> 00:10:47.510
J.L. COLLINS: Well, I'm
not sure I can answer that,

00:10:47.510 --> 00:10:51.990
because I can't put myself
in the heads of other people.

00:10:51.990 --> 00:10:54.240
Maybe I can answer
it by telling you

00:10:54.240 --> 00:10:57.050
why my advice is what
it is, and that's

00:10:57.050 --> 00:10:59.690
because I didn't write
this blog to have

00:10:59.690 --> 00:11:02.130
the international audience
that I have today.

00:11:02.130 --> 00:11:05.400
It never occurred to me
that that would happen.

00:11:05.400 --> 00:11:08.480
I had started actually
writing a series of letters

00:11:08.480 --> 00:11:11.977
to my daughter about financial
things I wanted her to know.

00:11:11.977 --> 00:11:14.060
And I shared it with a
business colleague of mine,

00:11:14.060 --> 00:11:17.067
and he said, you know, Jim,
this kind of interesting stuff.

00:11:17.067 --> 00:11:19.400
You might want to share it
with your friends and family,

00:11:19.400 --> 00:11:21.870
and a blog would be a
good way to do that.

00:11:21.870 --> 00:11:24.690
And this is in 2011.

00:11:24.690 --> 00:11:27.080
I like the idea of a blog,
because it occurred to me

00:11:27.080 --> 00:11:30.790
that it would be a great way
to archive the information.

00:11:30.790 --> 00:11:35.530
But I didn't have a plan to
create a blog as a business

00:11:35.530 --> 00:11:38.400
or as a successful way to
reach a broader audience.

00:11:38.400 --> 00:11:40.840
It was just to archive
the information

00:11:40.840 --> 00:11:42.610
I wanted my daughter to know.

00:11:42.610 --> 00:11:45.190
And that was basically
what mistakes

00:11:45.190 --> 00:11:47.800
I've made, what's worked,
what's kicked me in the ass,

00:11:47.800 --> 00:11:51.740
and what I think
specifically she should do.

00:11:51.740 --> 00:11:54.800
And so I think that's why
my advice is so specific.

00:11:54.800 --> 00:11:57.400
These are the things
that I'm doing now.

00:11:57.400 --> 00:12:00.980
These are things
I wish I had done

00:12:00.980 --> 00:12:05.210
in 1975, or at least in
1985, when I became aware

00:12:05.210 --> 00:12:06.320
of indexing.

00:12:06.320 --> 00:12:09.020
These are the things
that I want her to do

00:12:09.020 --> 00:12:11.060
and that I've got
her started doing.

00:12:11.060 --> 00:12:16.730
So that's maybe why my advice
is more specific than others.

00:12:16.730 --> 00:12:17.870
RACHEL SMITH: OK.

00:12:17.870 --> 00:12:19.760
I can't tell you
how many times I've

00:12:19.760 --> 00:12:23.110
talked with a friend about
how I'm on this new track

00:12:23.110 --> 00:12:25.610
where I'm investing, and they
say, well, what are you doing?

00:12:25.610 --> 00:12:27.560
And I just send
them one sentence

00:12:27.560 --> 00:12:29.210
of exactly what I'm
doing, and that's

00:12:29.210 --> 00:12:30.830
what I read in your book.

00:12:30.830 --> 00:12:32.020
And they're like, that's it?

00:12:32.020 --> 00:12:33.020
And I'm like, that's it.

00:12:33.020 --> 00:12:33.920
That's all I'm doing.

00:12:33.920 --> 00:12:37.550
So aside from telling them to
