So if you have a 401(k),
as you do at Google--

00:25:17.940 --> 00:25:20.440
and I have no idea what
your 401(k) looks like,

00:25:20.440 --> 00:25:23.920
but you will have a list of
selections of investments you

00:25:23.920 --> 00:25:27.250
can put in that 401(k) bucket.

00:25:27.250 --> 00:25:29.840
If my approach
resonates with you,

00:25:29.840 --> 00:25:34.210
and you believe in broad-based
index funds are something

00:25:34.210 --> 00:25:37.810
you want to go with, you
can go down that list

00:25:37.810 --> 00:25:42.180
and maybe find the specific
funds I'm talking about.

00:25:42.180 --> 00:25:43.750
But you will certainly
probably find

00:25:43.750 --> 00:25:47.110
something that is a
broad-based index fund.

00:25:47.110 --> 00:25:49.300
The easiest way to
do that, by the way,

00:25:49.300 --> 00:25:52.549
is to find the column that
shows the expense ratio.

00:25:52.549 --> 00:25:53.590
And you should have that.

00:25:53.590 --> 00:25:56.080
You run your finger
down that, and when

00:25:56.080 --> 00:25:58.570
you find the very
lowest expense ratios,

00:25:58.570 --> 00:26:00.460
you will have found
the index funds.

00:26:00.460 --> 00:26:04.092
And focus on those, and
take a look at them.

00:26:04.092 --> 00:26:06.300
RACHEL SMITH: And why do
you think some people choose

00:26:06.300 --> 00:26:09.120
to manage their own investments,
whereas others outsource it

00:26:09.120 --> 00:26:11.379
to someone else?

00:26:11.379 --> 00:26:13.670
J.L. COLLINS: Well, I think
the people who outsource it

00:26:13.670 --> 00:26:15.530
to someone else
have been convinced

00:26:15.530 --> 00:26:20.160
that this is just too complex
for their pretty little head.

00:26:20.160 --> 00:26:24.210
And the vast majority of
things on that banquet table

00:26:24.210 --> 00:26:28.320
we talked about are too complex
for anybody's pretty little

00:26:28.320 --> 00:26:29.930
head.

00:26:29.930 --> 00:26:34.960
In 2007, 2008, 2009 when
the economy cratered,

00:26:34.960 --> 00:26:38.700
Wall Street was selling
products they didn't understand.

00:26:38.700 --> 00:26:41.380
So if this stuff
looks complex to you,

00:26:41.380 --> 00:26:44.430
it's because this stuff is
complex, and in some cases,

00:26:44.430 --> 00:26:45.854
intentionally complex.

00:26:45.854 --> 00:26:47.520
But we don't care
about that, because we

00:26:47.520 --> 00:26:49.170
don't need any of that.

00:26:49.170 --> 00:26:53.010
And once you understand that you
don't need that complex stuff,

00:26:53.010 --> 00:26:57.150
then doing it yourself
becomes much more attainable,

00:26:57.150 --> 00:27:00.610
even if you don't have any
interest in financial stuff

00:27:00.610 --> 00:27:03.450
like, frankly, my daughter.

00:27:03.450 --> 00:27:05.940
She has better things to
do with her life than fool

00:27:05.940 --> 00:27:08.880
around with this financial
stuff that intrigues her dad,

00:27:08.880 --> 00:27:10.290
and that's great.

00:27:10.290 --> 00:27:16.710
People have bridges to build
and ways to make the world work.

00:27:16.710 --> 00:27:19.710
The beauty of this is that
if you get a couple of things

00:27:19.710 --> 00:27:22.500
right financially,
you can profoundly

00:27:22.500 --> 00:27:25.890
change your financial life
without having to dwell on it.

00:27:25.890 --> 00:27:27.420
And you can get on
with doing things

00:27:27.420 --> 00:27:29.086
that are more important
to you and maybe

00:27:29.086 --> 00:27:32.184
more important to the world.

00:27:32.184 --> 00:27:34.350
RACHEL SMITH: And what do
you think are two to three

00:27:34.350 --> 00:27:37.530
of the biggest mistakes
people can make when investing

00:27:37.530 --> 00:27:40.670
or managing their money?

00:27:40.670 --> 00:27:45.710
J.L. COLLINS: Well, I think
two come to mind immediately.

00:27:45.710 --> 00:27:51.630
One is thinking that you
can pick individual stocks,

00:27:51.630 --> 00:27:54.920
and by extension, that
you can pick people

00:27:54.920 --> 00:27:56.630
who can pick individual
stocks-- that is,

00:27:56.630 --> 00:28:01.890
people who run actively
managed mutual funds.

00:28:01.890 --> 00:28:06.620
One of the comments that
makes my skin crawl is when

00:28:06.620 --> 00:28:08.120
I hear people say
something like,

00:28:08.120 --> 00:28:11.030
well, Warren Buffett
became a billionaire

00:28:11.030 --> 00:28:12.420
picking individual stocks.

00:28:12.420 --> 00:28:14.850
I'll just do what Warren did.

00:28:14.850 --> 00:28:16.886
As if.

00:28:16.886 --> 00:28:17.790
As if.

00:28:17.790 --> 00:28:21.960
There is a reason that
Warren Buffett is famous,

00:28:21.960 --> 00:28:23.730
because Warren
Buffett has managed

00:28:23.730 --> 00:28:26.580
to do something that
is extraordinarily

00:28:26.580 --> 00:28:28.170
difficult to do.

00:28:28.170 --> 00:28:31.550
The ability to do it is
extraordinarily rare.

00:28:31.550 --> 00:28:35.940
And the hubris to think, oh,
I'll just go and do what Warren

00:28:35.940 --> 00:28:39.130
has done is, to me, stunning.

00:28:39.130 --> 00:28:40.380
It's just absolutely stunning.

00:28:40.380 --> 00:28:43.500
And the research indicates
that while Warren has done it,

00:28:43.500 --> 00:28:47.850
as we talked about, you go
out 30 years, and less than 1%

00:28:47.850 --> 00:28:50.190
of people trying to do
it who have survived

00:28:50.190 --> 00:28:52.200
that long have accomplished it.

00:28:55.120 --> 00:28:57.330
And I bring this one
up first, because this

00:28:57.330 --> 00:28:59.710
was my own stumbling block.

00:28:59.710 --> 00:29:01.890
I just kept believing
that I could

00:29:01.890 --> 00:29:04.350
pick people who
could pick stocks,

00:29:04.350 --> 00:29:06.980
and I believed that
I could pick stocks.

00:29:06.980 --> 00:29:09.740
And because every now and
again I'd get it right,

00:29:09.740 --> 00:29:13.350
and maybe I got it right more
often than I got it wrong,

00:29:13.350 --> 00:29:15.930
that feeds into that belief.

00:29:15.930 --> 00:29:17.400
And that's the
thing that made me

00:29:17.400 --> 00:29:19.710
reluctant to pick up indexing.

00:29:19.710 --> 00:29:23.220
But the truth is that the
few times I got it wrong

00:29:23.220 --> 00:29:26.700
dragged down my performance--

00:29:26.700 --> 00:29:29.010
and this is what happens to
the vast majority of people

00:29:29.010 --> 00:29:30.320
trying to do it--

00:29:30.320 --> 00:29:33.420
to where I would have been far
better off with the index--

00:29:33.420 --> 00:29:34.620
far better off.

00:29:34.620 --> 00:29:37.590
So trying to pick individual
stocks and managers is

00:29:37.590 --> 00:29:39.090
number one, maybe--

00:29:39.090 --> 00:29:40.740
not necessarily in order.

00:29:40.740 --> 00:29:43.380
The second thing is
trying to time the market.

00:29:43.380 --> 00:29:46.320
And you can't turn
on the financial news

00:29:46.320 --> 00:29:49.290
or open up a
financial periodical

00:29:49.290 --> 00:29:52.470
without finding somebody
who's telling you definitively

00:29:52.470 --> 00:29:54.990
where the stock
market is going next.

00:29:54.990 --> 00:29:56.310
Nobody knows.

00:29:56.310 --> 00:29:59.940
If you could accurately do
that with any consistency,

00:29:59.940 --> 00:30:03.360
you'd be far richer than Warren
Buffett and far more lionized.

00:30:03.360 --> 00:30:05.850
It would be magic dust.

00:30:05.850 --> 00:30:08.730
Nobody can tell you where
the market is going.

00:30:08.730 --> 00:30:12.520
You just can't predict
the market, and trying to

00:30:12.520 --> 00:30:15.300
is a fool's game.

00:30:15.300 --> 00:30:18.855
So Fidelity Investments did
a little piece of research

00:30:18.855 --> 00:30:21.620
I think about a year ago,
a year and a half ago,

00:30:21.620 --> 00:30:24.960
and they were curious as
to what group of investors

00:30:24.960 --> 00:30:27.900
in their funds did best.

00:30:27.900 --> 00:30:29.970
Because the research
indicates that the people

00:30:29.970 --> 00:30:36.000
who invest in a mutual
fund under-perform

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:38.280
the performance of that fund.

00:30:38.280 --> 00:30:39.780
He said, well, how
is that possible?

00:30:39.780 --> 00:30:41.610
If they're investing
in the fund,

00:30:41.610 --> 00:30:44.220
their performance
should match the fund.

00:30:44.220 --> 00:30:47.230
The reason they under-perform
is they try to dance in and out.

00:30:47.230 --> 00:30:49.110
They tried to time the market.

00:30:49.110 --> 00:30:52.260
So when Fidelity
did this research,

00:30:52.260 --> 00:30:55.660
they determined that
one group of investors

00:30:55.660 --> 00:30:59.390
did significantly better
than any other group who

00:30:59.390 --> 00:31:00.570
own their funds--

00:31:00.570 --> 00:31:02.990
and that was dead people.

00:31:02.990 --> 00:31:05.540
The dead people outperformed.

00:31:05.540 --> 00:31:07.470
Now, can you guess why?

00:31:07.470 --> 00:31:10.500
Because they didn't tinker
with their investment.

00:31:10.500 --> 00:31:12.099
The second best
performing group were

00:31:12.099 --> 00:31:13.890
people who forgot that
they owned the fund.

00:31:16.650 --> 00:31:19.950
So you can't time the
market, and especially

00:31:19.950 --> 00:31:23.889
when the market has been on
as long a bull run as it has.

00:31:23.889 --> 00:31:25.680
The media is filled
with people telling you

00:31:25.680 --> 00:31:28.730
that they know what
it's going to do next.

00:31:28.730 --> 00:31:31.220
At some point, the
market will dive,

00:31:31.220 --> 00:31:33.530
because the market is volatile.

00:31:33.530 --> 00:31:35.000
That's what markets do.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:38.360
So if you invest in the market,
you have to expect that.

00:31:38.360 --> 00:31:40.610
You have to expect
the volatility.

00:31:40.610 --> 00:31:43.520
You have to be willing
to ride with it.

00:31:43.520 --> 00:31:45.600
But I don't know when
it's going to do that.

00:31:45.600 --> 00:31:48.260
It could be happening as we're
sitting in this room together

00:31:48.260 --> 00:31:49.040
today.

00:31:49.040 --> 00:31:51.040
I haven't looked at the market.

00:31:51.040 --> 00:31:52.350
It might be 10 years from now.

00:31:52.350 --> 00:31:54.700
I have no idea, and
nobody else knows.

00:31:54.700 --> 00:31:58.490
The difference is I'm
willing to say I don't know.

00:31:58.490 --> 00:32:00.120
RACHEL SMITH: So
for someone who may

00:32:00.120 --> 00:32:03.820
be interested in investing--
maybe when they go home today.

00:32:03.820 --> 00:32:07.180
They have some cash they
want to start investing.

00:32:07.180 --> 00:32:09.890
And they say, well, the market's
the highest it's ever been.

00:32:09.890 --> 00:32:12.910
I'm going to wait for it to dip.

00:32:12.910 --> 00:32:15.580
What advice would you
give to those folks who

00:32:15.580 --> 00:32:17.080
are waiting for the next step?

00:32:23.630 --> 00:32:26.990
J.L. COLLINS: If we went
back to March of 2009,

00:32:26.990 --> 00:32:30.095
which was when the market
bottomed and its collapse.

00:32:34.420 --> 00:32:36.709
Almost every month
since then, you

00:32:36.709 --> 00:32:38.000
could have said the same thing.

00:32:40.510 --> 00:32:42.190
I wrote a post
in, I want to say,

00:32:42.190 --> 00:32:46.120
2014 responding to a
reader who was asking

00:32:46.120 --> 00:32:47.980
that exact same question.

00:32:47.980 --> 00:32:52.240
The S&amp;P 500 was
1,600 and change,

00:32:52.240 --> 00:32:55.810
and this reader was saying,
how can I possibly reinvest?

00:32:55.810 --> 00:32:57.700
How can I possibly invest?

00:32:57.700 --> 00:32:59.580
Nothing would go up for
the last five years.

00:32:59.580 --> 00:33:02.740
And here it is at 1,600,
and it bottomed out

00:33:02.740 --> 00:33:06.310
at I want to say
600 and something.

00:33:06.310 --> 00:33:07.580
And where are we today?

00:33:07.580 --> 00:33:09.820
Now, I didn't know
that at the time,

00:33:09.820 --> 00:33:12.580
because I didn't know where
the market was going to go.

00:33:12.580 --> 00:33:13.630
But you just don't know.

00:33:13.630 --> 00:33:15.410
You can't predict the market.

00:33:15.410 --> 00:33:19.930
And by the way, it's become
fashionable to suggest

00:33:19.930 --> 00:33:22.960
the P/E ratios or
Shiller P/E ratios give

00:33:22.960 --> 00:33:24.940
some insight into this.

00:33:24.940 --> 00:33:30.210
In that post-- it's called
"Investing in a raging bull,"

00:33:30.210 --> 00:33:31.360
it's in the stock series--

00:33:35.410 --> 00:33:40.990
I just put a link to
a post I came across--

00:33:40.990 --> 00:33:43.750
very well done--
where the guy analyzes

00:33:43.750 --> 00:33:49.430
where the various P/E ratios
were at the beginning of drops.

00:33:49.430 --> 00:33:55.450
And there's no predictive
correlation there to be had,

00:33:55.450 --> 00:33:59.440
so you just can't know.

00:33:59.440 --> 00:34:03.850
I also have a post called
"Why I don't like dollar cost

00:34:03.850 --> 00:34:05.330
averaging."

00:34:05.330 --> 00:34:10.310
And in summary,
dollar cost averaging

00:34:10.310 --> 00:34:12.590
is the idea of putting
in a little bit of money

00:34:12.590 --> 00:34:16.230
at a time over a period of time.

00:34:16.230 --> 00:34:19.610
The problem with that is that
unless the market conveniently

00:34:19.610 --> 00:34:21.702
goes down while
you're doing it, you

00:34:21.702 --> 00:34:25.520
will have been giving up gains
rather than avoiding losses.

00:34:25.520 --> 00:34:27.020
And the thing that
really bothers me

00:34:27.020 --> 00:34:29.989
about it is that at the end
of your investment period

00:34:29.989 --> 00:34:33.110
where you have finally deployed
all of your money, who's

00:34:33.110 --> 00:34:35.630
to say the next
day isn't the day

00:34:35.630 --> 00:34:38.179
the market takes its big plunge?

00:34:38.179 --> 00:34:41.870
So you have $120,000,
you want to deploy.

00:34:41.870 --> 00:34:44.530
and you say, I'm going to do
it over the next 12 months.

00:34:44.530 --> 00:34:48.440
And I'm going to put
$10,000 a month in,

00:34:48.440 --> 00:34:50.120
and I'm going to
avoid that risk.

00:34:50.120 --> 00:34:51.620
You're not avoiding
the risk, you're

00:34:51.620 --> 00:34:55.949
just delaying the risk until
you put that final $10,000 in.

00:34:55.949 --> 00:34:58.040
Now, if you get lucky
and the market plunges,

00:34:58.040 --> 00:34:59.390
you'll pat yourself on the back.

00:34:59.390 --> 00:35:02.360
But understand that's only
luck, because nobody knows

00:35:02.360 --> 00:35:03.950
where the market is going.

00:35:03.950 --> 00:35:07.160
There's a saying that the
best time to have invested

00:35:07.160 --> 00:35:11.603
was yesterday, and the
second best time is today.

00:35:11.603 --> 00:35:13.730
RACHEL SMITH:
That's great advice

00:35:13.730 --> 00:35:15.800
J.L. COLLINS: Time in the
market is more powerful

00:35:15.800 --> 00:35:17.822
than to time the market.

00:35:17.822 --> 00:35:19.280
RACHEL SMITH: Time
in the market is

00:35:19.280 --> 00:35:22.291
more powerful than trying
to time the market.

00:35:22.291 --> 00:35:23.290
J.L. COLLINS: Well said.

00:35:23.290 --> 00:35:25.280
RACHEL SMITH: I like that.

00:35:25.280 --> 00:35:27.450
So we have one more
question for Jim,

00:35:27.450 --> 00:35:29.960
but for folks who
have live questions,

00:35:29.960 --> 00:35:31.760
feel free to line up at the mic.

00:35:31.760 --> 00:35:35.690
We also have a Dory at
go slash Jim dash Dory.

00:35:35.690 --> 00:35:39.980
So my last question before we
turn it over to live questions

00:35:39.980 --> 00:35:41.930
is, there may be
folks in this room who

00:35:41.930 --> 00:35:43.700
have a New Year's
resolution to get

00:35:43.700 --> 00:35:46.040
their financial house in order.

00:35:46.040 --> 00:35:49.200
And they may be one
of the folks who

00:35:49.200 --> 00:35:52.100
have a lot of cash in
checking or savings,

00:35:52.100 --> 00:35:54.212
or they just are so
overwhelmed by this stuff

00:35:54.212 --> 00:35:55.920
that they don't even
know where to begin.

00:35:55.920 --> 00:35:58.580
So what would you say are
just the key takeaways

00:35:58.580 --> 00:36:02.450
they should focus on when
they leave this room?

00:36:02.450 --> 00:36:05.930
J.L. COLLINS: Well, again,
I would encourage anybody

00:36:05.930 --> 00:36:08.480
in that position-- if you're
sitting on that much cash,

00:36:08.480 --> 00:36:11.030
and assuming that
that amount of cash

00:36:11.030 --> 00:36:13.490
represents a large
part of your net worth,

00:36:13.490 --> 00:36:14.900
because money is relative.

00:36:14.900 --> 00:36:18.560
But if you're sitting on
$100,000 as an example,

00:36:18.560 --> 00:36:21.320
and that is a large
part of your net worth,

00:36:21.320 --> 00:36:23.580
that indicates that you're
not comfortable investing.

00:36:23.580 --> 00:36:24.260
And that's fine.

00:36:24.260 --> 00:36:27.320
So the first thing you should
do is educate yourself,

00:36:27.320 --> 00:36:30.890
and you can start with
my blog or my book.

00:36:30.890 --> 00:36:33.590
And see if that resonates,
and go from there.

00:36:33.590 --> 00:36:35.540
If you find it doesn't
resonate, then there

00:36:35.540 --> 00:36:37.950
are a lot of other
sources out there,

00:36:37.950 --> 00:36:39.380
but educate yourself first.

00:36:42.400 --> 00:36:44.090
And some of the posts
that I referenced

00:36:44.090 --> 00:36:46.010
are in the stock series.

00:36:46.010 --> 00:36:48.440
You can read about
investing in a raging bull.

00:36:48.440 --> 00:36:53.030
You can read about
dollar cost averaging.

00:36:53.030 --> 00:36:55.040
But once you decide
to invest in stocks,

00:36:55.040 --> 00:37:00.020
you have to accept the fact
that the market is volatile.

00:37:00.020 --> 00:37:02.300
At some point, the
market will go down.

00:37:02.300 --> 00:37:04.370
Now, whether it goes
down 10% and continues

00:37:04.370 --> 00:37:06.600
going up 20%, who knows.

00:37:06.600 --> 00:37:07.700
Nobody knows.

00:37:07.700 --> 00:37:10.300
But the market-- you can
count on it being volatile.

00:37:10.300 --> 00:37:12.080
And at some point,
it will go down,

00:37:12.080 --> 00:37:14.450
and you have to come
to terms with that.

00:37:14.450 --> 00:37:18.950
And you have to be absolutely
sure that when that happens--

00:37:18.950 --> 00:37:20.630
not if, but when--

00:37:20.630 --> 00:37:22.370
you don't panic.

00:37:22.370 --> 00:37:25.130
Because the only way
you lose is if you

00:37:25.130 --> 00:37:28.160
panic and sell at the bottom.

00:37:28.160 --> 00:37:30.890
Now, trust me when I
tell you, because I've

00:37:30.890 --> 00:37:32.510
lived through a few of them.

00:37:32.510 --> 00:37:35.870
When the market is taking
one of its dives, it's ugly.

00:37:35.870 --> 00:37:36.680
It's painful.

00:37:36.680 --> 00:37:37.730
It's scary.

00:37:37.730 --> 00:37:39.890
It's easy to sit here
now and say, well, I'll

00:37:39.890 --> 00:37:41.330
stay the course.

00:37:41.330 --> 00:37:44.880
But it's not so easy to
do it when it's happening.

00:37:44.880 --> 00:37:48.560
So the first thing
you need to resolve

00:37:48.560 --> 00:37:51.200
it seems to me in your own
mind, in your own heart,

00:37:51.200 --> 00:37:55.430
in your own gut, is
that when that happens,

00:37:55.430 --> 00:37:58.520
that selling is not an option.

00:37:58.520 --> 00:38:01.670
It's just simply not an option.

00:38:01.670 --> 00:38:05.330
Now, in my world,
I divide the times

00:38:05.330 --> 00:38:08.870
in our life between wealth
accumulation and wealth

00:38:08.870 --> 00:38:11.360
preservation stages.

00:38:11.360 --> 00:38:13.190
In a more traditional
point in time,

00:38:13.190 --> 00:38:15.800
that might have been when
you're young and you're working,

00:38:15.800 --> 00:38:19.460
that's your wealth
building stage.

00:38:19.460 --> 00:38:22.310
And then you get to
60 or 65, and you

00:38:22.310 --> 00:38:24.170
retire, wealth preservation.

00:38:24.170 --> 00:38:26.150
These days, people
step in and out

00:38:26.150 --> 00:38:28.700
of careers on a
routine basis, so you

00:38:28.700 --> 00:38:31.220
will go from wealth
preservation to wealth building

00:38:31.220 --> 00:38:32.810
and back several times.

00:38:32.810 --> 00:38:34.970
I know I did in my career.

00:38:34.970 --> 00:38:37.460
When you're doing that,
there are two ways

00:38:37.460 --> 00:38:40.310
you can mitigate the
volatility of the market

00:38:40.310 --> 00:38:43.270
and actually use it
to your advantage.

00:38:43.270 --> 00:38:46.900
When you are in the
wealth building stage,

00:38:46.900 --> 00:38:48.580
you have earned income.

00:38:48.580 --> 00:38:51.250
And if you're aiming to be
financially independent,

00:38:51.250 --> 00:38:54.520
a large portion of
that income is being

00:38:54.520 --> 00:38:56.560
diverted into investments.

00:38:56.560 --> 00:38:58.480
So that means on
a regular basis,

00:38:58.480 --> 00:39:01.150
you are putting substantial
amounts of your income

00:39:01.150 --> 00:39:02.950
into the market.

00:39:02.950 --> 00:39:05.800
That, by extension, means
when the market drops,

00:39:05.800 --> 00:39:07.650
you're getting to
buy things on sale.

00:39:07.650 --> 00:39:09.400
Now, you're not going
to try to time this,

00:39:09.400 --> 00:39:11.050
because we know
we can't do that.

00:39:11.050 --> 00:39:14.110
But what it does mean is
that when the market drops,

00:39:14.110 --> 00:39:15.520
you should celebrate.

00:39:15.520 --> 00:39:19.480
Because, oh, I'm getting to buy,
when I put that extra $1,000

00:39:19.480 --> 00:39:22.540
or $10,000 or whatever
it is in each month,

00:39:22.540 --> 00:39:26.200
I'm getting more
shares in my VTSAX

00:39:26.200 --> 00:39:27.940
than I would have
gotten otherwise.

00:39:27.940 --> 00:39:31.550
The volatility works to your
advantage in that fashion.

00:39:31.550 --> 00:39:34.090
So you sleep easily at
night, because you don't care

00:39:34.090 --> 00:39:35.880
what Mr. Market's going to do.

00:39:35.880 --> 00:39:39.610
Now, when you move to the
wealth preservation stage,

00:39:39.610 --> 00:39:43.360
you no longer have that income
stream to smooth the ride.

00:39:43.360 --> 00:39:47.060
And that, in my world,
is when you add bonds,

00:39:47.060 --> 00:39:50.660
and bonds become like
ballast in your sailing ship.

00:39:50.660 --> 00:39:54.230
Where your flow of
income was before,

00:39:54.230 --> 00:39:57.590
now you're going to replace
that with the ballast of bonds.

00:39:57.590 --> 00:40:00.620
And that means that
when the market plunges,

00:40:00.620 --> 00:40:03.920
the stocks plunge,
and you reallocate

00:40:03.920 --> 00:40:06.590
to stay at whatever
allocation you've chosen,

00:40:06.590 --> 00:40:09.140
you'll be selling bonds,
which have gone up

00:40:09.140 --> 00:40:12.000
as a percentage
of your portfolio.

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:14.900
Let's say, as I do at
the moment, you have 30%

00:40:14.900 --> 00:40:18.530
bonds, 70% stocks.

00:40:18.530 --> 00:40:20.780
When stocks plummet,
that percentage of bonds

00:40:20.780 --> 00:40:21.980
is going to go up.

00:40:21.980 --> 00:40:25.250
You sell some of those bonds,
and you're buying those stocks

00:40:25.250 --> 00:40:28.880
at lower prices, just
like your cash flow was

00:40:28.880 --> 00:40:30.710
allowing you to do it before.

00:40:30.710 --> 00:40:34.490
When stocks go back up again
and suddenly that percentage

00:40:34.490 --> 00:40:37.850
of stocks start to outweigh
where you want it to be--

00:40:37.850 --> 00:40:39.260
it gets above 70%--

00:40:39.260 --> 00:40:42.530
you start selling some of those
off to replenish your bonds.

00:40:42.530 --> 00:40:44.720
With those two
strategies, you no longer

00:40:44.720 --> 00:40:48.470
have to care whether the
market is going up or down,

00:40:48.470 --> 00:40:52.130
because you know that over time
the market is going to go up.

00:40:52.130 --> 00:40:55.320
And you've eliminated the
concerns with volatility.

00:40:55.320 --> 00:40:58.420
So I would embrace
those two concepts--

00:40:58.420 --> 00:41:02.270
understand that you don't
ever sell in a panic

00:41:02.270 --> 00:41:03.830
just because it went down.

00:41:03.830 --> 00:41:07.280
That is simply not an option
that you will ever consider.

00:41:07.280 --> 00:41:09.950
And then depending on
which stage you're in,

00:41:09.950 --> 00:41:13.440
either use bonds or use cash
flow to smooth the ride.

00:41:13.440 --> 00:41:14.440
