00:51:17.450 --> 00:51:21.030
And two, that they
didn't need to worry,

00:51:21.030 --> 00:51:26.430
because the world was filled
with other companies waiting

00:51:26.430 --> 00:51:30.840
to eat General Motors' lunch
the moment they slipped up--

00:51:30.840 --> 00:51:33.240
or simply the moment the
competitor figured out

00:51:33.240 --> 00:51:35.140
a better way to do it.

00:51:35.140 --> 00:51:38.010
So you have to be very careful
in putting all of your eggs

00:51:38.010 --> 00:51:41.890
into the same basket
where you work.

00:51:41.890 --> 00:51:44.230
Going back to the question
the gentleman asked earlier

00:51:44.230 --> 00:51:49.840
about the S&amp;P 500, I would
rather own the S&amp;P 500--

00:51:49.840 --> 00:51:53.980
or at least have the bulk of
my net worth in the S&amp;P 500--

00:51:53.980 --> 00:51:58.020
because now I don't have to
guess who's going to win.

00:51:58.020 --> 00:52:03.080
Because the losers fall off, and
the winners go on to prosper.

00:52:03.080 --> 00:52:04.940
One of the beautiful
things about the index

00:52:04.940 --> 00:52:08.630
is what I call self-cleansing.

00:52:08.630 --> 00:52:12.860
And by that, what I
mean is that if you

00:52:12.860 --> 00:52:17.840
look at any specific
company in that index,

00:52:17.840 --> 00:52:22.290
you can only lose
100% of that company.

00:52:22.290 --> 00:52:24.020
But any other company
in that index--

00:52:24.020 --> 00:52:25.550
and Google is a
wonderful example

00:52:25.550 --> 00:52:27.710
of this over the
last few decades--

00:52:27.710 --> 00:52:29.430
can grow exponentially.

00:52:29.430 --> 00:52:32.630
There is almost no limit
to how far it can grow.

00:52:32.630 --> 00:52:34.880
So that's kind of a
winning combination.

00:52:34.880 --> 00:52:37.880
The losers fall off, and they
don't actually go to 100%

00:52:37.880 --> 00:52:39.650
before they get delisted.

00:52:39.650 --> 00:52:42.830
But the losers drift away,
and you are continually

00:52:42.830 --> 00:52:46.430
getting new blood added to
it as new companies come up.

00:52:46.430 --> 00:52:49.070
And you get the benefit
from those who succeed,

00:52:49.070 --> 00:52:50.630
and all those
companies are filled

00:52:50.630 --> 00:52:53.480
with people who are
working hard to make sure

00:52:53.480 --> 00:52:55.190
that their company succeeds.

00:52:55.190 --> 00:52:57.800
And as an investor, I
don't have to figure out

00:52:57.800 --> 00:53:02.920
who the winner is going to
be, because I own them all.

00:53:02.920 --> 00:53:06.040
RACHEL SMITH: We have time
for one more question.

00:53:06.040 --> 00:53:10.700
AUDIENCE: So I was going to ask
two, but I think they're quick.

00:53:10.700 --> 00:53:15.040
The retirement-date
funds-- thoughts on those

00:53:15.040 --> 00:53:16.750
target retirement-date funds?

00:53:16.750 --> 00:53:18.930
So automatically adjusting
allocations as you're

00:53:18.930 --> 00:53:20.602
closer to retirement--

00:53:20.602 --> 00:53:21.310
thoughts on that?

00:53:21.310 --> 00:53:23.620
Or do you think you should
just do allocation yourself

00:53:23.620 --> 00:53:29.620
through the various bonds and
Vanguard funds on your own?

00:53:29.620 --> 00:53:32.155
And then the second one was
just really about in what

00:53:32.155 --> 00:53:34.140
scenarios would you
find it helpful to use

00:53:34.140 --> 00:53:35.087
a financial advisor.

00:53:35.087 --> 00:53:37.420
I find doing it on your own
is great, but at some point,

00:53:37.420 --> 00:53:38.800
you want some kind
of reassurance

00:53:38.800 --> 00:53:40.030
you're doing it well--

00:53:40.030 --> 00:53:42.910
not for investment banking,
but you have to go to someone

00:53:42.910 --> 00:53:46.240
to get insurance, et cetera.

00:53:46.240 --> 00:53:49.480
J.L. COLLINS: OK, so a
target retirement fund,

00:53:49.480 --> 00:53:51.670
just to kind of quickly
explain what that is.

00:53:51.670 --> 00:53:53.680
There are mutual
funds out there--

00:53:53.680 --> 00:53:57.340
Vanguard has them-- which are
called target-date retirement

00:53:57.340 --> 00:53:59.020
funds or target
retirement funds.

00:53:59.020 --> 00:54:05.440
And the idea is that it's what's
called a fund of funds, which

00:54:05.440 --> 00:54:07.840
means it is a mutual
fund that holds

00:54:07.840 --> 00:54:09.490
a bunch of other
funds inside it,

00:54:09.490 --> 00:54:13.750
usually five or six
different funds.

00:54:13.750 --> 00:54:15.460
And with a target
retirement fund,

00:54:15.460 --> 00:54:19.090
you pick a retirement
date, and you buy the fund.

00:54:19.090 --> 00:54:21.220
And as the gentleman
just indicated,

00:54:21.220 --> 00:54:22.860
you can hold it forever.

00:54:22.860 --> 00:54:26.530
And automatically, the closer
you get to that retirement

00:54:26.530 --> 00:54:31.240
date, the more conservative the
fund allocation will become--

00:54:31.240 --> 00:54:35.200
that is to say, typically
the more bonds they will add.

00:54:35.200 --> 00:54:39.040
So the idea is you never have
to adjust your allocation as you

00:54:39.040 --> 00:54:40.710
get to it.

00:54:40.710 --> 00:54:43.570
Now, so some people
say, well, gee, I

00:54:43.570 --> 00:54:46.540
might want to be more
aggressive or less aggressive

00:54:46.540 --> 00:54:49.130
than the retirement fund.

00:54:49.130 --> 00:54:50.440
Well, you can adjust that.

00:54:50.440 --> 00:54:52.060
If you want to be
more aggressive,

00:54:52.060 --> 00:54:54.170
just pick one with
a retirement date

00:54:54.170 --> 00:54:57.220
that's actually further out
than your own anticipated

00:54:57.220 --> 00:54:58.270
retirement.

00:54:58.270 --> 00:55:00.470
If you want to be
more conservative,

00:55:00.470 --> 00:55:02.770
you can just bring
that retirement date in

00:55:02.770 --> 00:55:07.350
closer than you were
actually planning to retire.

00:55:07.350 --> 00:55:10.360
And the idea is that you never
have to do anything again.

00:55:14.050 --> 00:55:15.430
It is not a bad approach.

00:55:15.430 --> 00:55:18.970
If you really want to invest in
a way that is completely hands

00:55:18.970 --> 00:55:22.090
off where you really never
have to think about it,

00:55:22.090 --> 00:55:23.650
this is not a bad way to go.

00:55:23.650 --> 00:55:26.950
And in fact, I have a post
on this in the stock series,

00:55:26.950 --> 00:55:28.730
and I think it's a
chapter in the book.

00:55:28.730 --> 00:55:30.570
I'm not sure if I put
it in the book or not.

00:55:30.570 --> 00:55:32.140
But there is a post
in the stock series

00:55:32.140 --> 00:55:33.520
where I talk about these things.

00:55:33.520 --> 00:55:36.130
It's not a bad way to go.

00:55:36.130 --> 00:55:38.140
What I suggest to
people is that if you

00:55:38.140 --> 00:55:40.690
can read through my
stock series and you're

00:55:40.690 --> 00:55:43.480
comfortable with what you
read, or you read my blog--

00:55:43.480 --> 00:55:46.720
or my book, rather-- and you're
comfortable with what you read,

00:55:46.720 --> 00:55:52.330
it is less expensive to simply
do the allocation yourself.

00:55:52.330 --> 00:55:53.690
And it's not very hard.

00:55:53.690 --> 00:55:55.060
It doesn't take much time.

00:55:55.060 --> 00:55:57.530
And that's the way I
would encourage you to go.

00:55:57.530 --> 00:55:59.977
On the other hand, if you
read through the stock series

00:55:59.977 --> 00:56:01.810
or you start reading
through it and you say,

00:56:01.810 --> 00:56:05.740
you know what, I just
really don't want to.

00:56:05.740 --> 00:56:08.230
This is just not my thing--

00:56:08.230 --> 00:56:10.240
and there are topics,
by the way, in my life

00:56:10.240 --> 00:56:12.190
that I would have
that reaction to--

00:56:12.190 --> 00:56:16.060
then just skip down to the post
about target retirement funds

00:56:16.060 --> 00:56:18.520
and you can be done.

00:56:18.520 --> 00:56:21.576
It won't be a bad thing to do.

00:56:21.576 --> 00:56:23.950
And the second thing, real
quickly, in terms of financial

00:56:23.950 --> 00:56:25.210
advisors--

00:56:25.210 --> 00:56:26.680
again, I don't
think you need them.

00:56:26.680 --> 00:56:28.390
If you follow an
approach like mine,

00:56:28.390 --> 00:56:32.390
which is simple investing,
you don't need them for that.

00:56:32.390 --> 00:56:36.520
But there are other aspects
where they can be useful.

00:56:36.520 --> 00:56:38.260
The problem with
financial advisors

00:56:38.260 --> 00:56:41.830
is while there are good ones,
there are a lot who are not.

00:56:41.830 --> 00:56:44.240
And they're not for
a couple of reasons.

00:56:44.240 --> 00:56:46.740
One is simply they're
not that competent.

00:56:46.740 --> 00:56:49.600
But the other-- and a
little more insidious--

00:56:49.600 --> 00:56:53.230
is that their interests
are not necessarily aligned

00:56:53.230 --> 00:56:55.000
with what's best for you.

00:56:55.000 --> 00:56:59.920
So if you read my post on why I
don't like investment advisors,

00:56:59.920 --> 00:57:02.140
one of the conclusions
I come to is

00:57:02.140 --> 00:57:06.610
by the time you know enough
to choose an investment

00:57:06.610 --> 00:57:11.050
advisor wisely, had you invested
that time learning it yourself,

00:57:11.050 --> 00:57:13.960
you would know enough
to do it on your own.

